When a user tries to navigate to a page they are not permitted to see or to a page they have bookmarked which has since moved, Confluence redirects them to the page not found page. 

Once there, it tries to search for page alternatives. It currently does this on a global level in addition to space, trash and search. 

We should not search globally as it can be very expensive to filter on all the unpermitted results that come back.

Please also see the attached screenshot of the javascript error as it appears in firefox. Error again is: 

{noformat}
response has no properties
{noformat}

This problem may not actually be isolated to attachment migration but extend to all long running tasks. 

This error strangely cannot be reproduced locally but only a particular customer's production instance (even they were not able to reproduce the problem in their test environment)

When using the [Dynamic LDAP Group plugin|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONFEXT/LDAP+Dynamic+Groups+Plugin], on a clustered-version of Confluence (2.5.5), the following problem was reported:
Before creating any content in Confluence, when a LDAP user logs into Confluence, all the local and LDAP groups, that this user belongs to are listed correctly for this user in the "User Browser" screen.
After creating content in Confluence, all LDAP groups disappear and now the user is listed as a member of only the *confluence-users* group. As a result all permissions related to the LDAP groups are revoked. 
This problem was not reproducible on a Standalone version of Confluence.

We need to determine whether it is related to the plugin or to our group user management system as the plugin java code does not seem to be doing anything 'funky' with assigning content to users or groups? It just simply assigns an LDAp user to the {{confluence-users}} group upon login as per source snippet below. _Bit of a mystery at the moment_ 

{code:java}
while (iter.hasNext()) {
				String groupName = (String)iter.next();
				User user = getUserAccessor().getUser(username);
				try {
					Group confluenceGroup = getGroupManager().getGroup(groupName);
					if (confluenceGroup == null) {
						log.error("Could not find confluence group by name: " + groupName);
					}
					if (!getGroupManager().hasMembership(confluenceGroup, user)) {
						getGroupManager().addMembership(confluenceGroup, user);
					}
				}
				catch (EntityException e) {
					log.error("Failed to add " + username + " to " + groupName + ": " + e.getMessage(), e);
				}
			}
		}
{code}

 We need to investigate this.
Please refer to the attached screenshots for more details.

